questions.answer:
Compilers add padding bytes to align struct members to their natural boundaries (e.g., a `uint32_t` aligns to a 4-byte boundary). This improves CPU access speed but wastes memory.

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdint.h>

// Normal struct — compiler adds padding
struct Unpacked {
    uint8_t  a;  // 1 byte + 3 padding
    uint32_t b;  // 4 bytes
    uint8_t  c;  // 1 byte + 3 padding
}; // Total: 12 bytes

// Packed struct — no padding
struct __attribute__((packed)) Packed {
    uint8_t  a;  // 1 byte
    uint32_t b;  // 4 bytes (possibly unaligned!)
    uint8_t  c;  // 1 byte
}; // Total: 6 bytes

int main() {
    printf("Unpacked: %zu bytes\n", sizeof(struct Unpacked)); // 12
    printf("Packed:   %zu bytes\n", sizeof(struct Packed));   // 6
    return 0;
}
```

**When to pack:** Wire protocols, file formats, hardware register maps — anywhere the struct layout must match an external binary format.

**Danger:** Unaligned access. On ARM Cortex-M, unaligned 32-bit reads may fault or silently corrupt data depending on the core. Use `memcpy` or byte-level access for safety.

