questions.answer:
**What happened:**
A slave device got confused mid-transaction (master reset during a read, power glitch, noise on SCL) and is still driving SDA low — it thinks it's in the middle of sending a byte. The master can't issue a START condition because SDA is held low.

**This is the #1 I2C field problem.** It affects every I2C system eventually.

**Recovery procedure (clock recovery):**
```c
void i2c_bus_recovery(void) {
    // 1. Configure SDA and SCL as GPIO (not I2C peripheral)
    gpio_set_mode(SCL_PIN, GPIO_OUTPUT_OD); // Open-drain
    gpio_set_mode(SDA_PIN, GPIO_INPUT);     // Monitor SDA

    // 2. Toggle SCL up to 9 times
    //    The stuck slave will release SDA after clocking out
    //    the remaining bits of whatever byte it was sending
    for (int i = 0; i < 9; i++) {
        if (gpio_read(SDA_PIN)) break; // SDA released, done
        gpio_write(SCL_PIN, 0);
        delay_us(5);
        gpio_write(SCL_PIN, 1);
        delay_us(5);
    }

    // 3. Generate a STOP condition
    gpio_set_mode(SDA_PIN, GPIO_OUTPUT_OD);
    gpio_write(SDA_PIN, 0);
    delay_us(5);
    gpio_write(SCL_PIN, 1);
    delay_us(5);
    gpio_write(SDA_PIN, 1); // SDA rising while SCL high = STOP

    // 4. Reconfigure pins back to I2C peripheral mode
    i2c_init();
}
```

**Why 9 clocks?** A byte is 8 bits + 1 ACK. In the worst case, the slave has 8 more bits to send before it releases SDA for the ACK cycle.

**Prevention:**
- Always implement I2C timeout in your driver (don't block forever waiting for ACK)
- Run bus recovery on initialization (board might have been reset mid-transfer)
- Use hardware I2C peripherals that support bus recovery natively (STM32 has this)
- Consider pull-up resistor values — too weak and rise times are slow, too strong and low-drive devices can't pull SDA down

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>
#include <stdbool.h>

typedef void (*cmd_handler_t)(const char *args);

typedef struct {
    const char *name;
    cmd_handler_t handler;
    const char *help;
} Command;

static void cmd_led(const char *args) {
    if (strcmp(args, "on") == 0)
        printf("LED: ON\n");
    else if (strcmp(args, "off") == 0)
        printf("LED: OFF\n");
    else
        printf("Usage: led <on|off>\n");
}

static void cmd_status(const char *args) {
    (void)args;
    printf("System: running\nUptime: 12345 ticks\nTemp: 42C\n");
}

static void cmd_reset(const char *args) {
    (void)args;
    printf("Resetting...\n");
    // In real firmware: NVIC_SystemReset();
}

static void cmd_help(const char *args);

static const Command commands[] = {
    { "led",    cmd_led,    "Control LED (on/off)" },
    { "status", cmd_status, "Show system status" },
    { "reset",  cmd_reset,  "Reset the device" },
    { "help",   cmd_help,   "Show available commands" },
};
#define CMD_COUNT (sizeof(commands) / sizeof(commands[0]))

static void cmd_help(const char *args) {
    (void)args;
    for (size_t i = 0; i < CMD_COUNT; i++)
        printf("  %-10s %s\n", commands[i].name, commands[i].help);
}

void parse_command(char *line) {
    // Skip leading whitespace
    while (*line == ' ') line++;
    if (*line == '\0') return;

    // Split command and args
    char *args = strchr(line, ' ');
    if (args) {
        *args = '\0';
        args++;
        while (*args == ' ') args++;
    } else {
        args = "";
    }

    // Lookup and dispatch
    for (size_t i = 0; i < CMD_COUNT; i++) {
        if (strcmp(line, commands[i].name) == 0) {
            commands[i].handler(args);
            return;
        }
    }
    printf("Unknown command: '%s'. Type 'help'.\n", line);
}
```

**Key design patterns:**
- **Table-driven dispatch** — adding a command is just adding a table entry, no switch/case sprawl
- **Function pointers** — each command is a callback, easily unit-testable
- **Separation of parsing from handling** — parse_command doesn't know what commands do
- In real firmware, you'd build the input line from UART RX byte-by-byte (ring buffer → line buffer, process on '\n')
- Consider adding command history (up arrow) and tab completion for a production debug console

