```c
uint32_t reverse_bits(uint32_t x) {
    x = ((x & 0xFFFF0000) >> 16) | ((x & 0x0000FFFF) << 16);
    x = ((x & 0xFF00FF00) >> 8)  | ((x & 0x00FF00FF) << 8);
    x = ((x & 0xF0F0F0F0) >> 4)  | ((x & 0x0F0F0F0F) << 4);
    x = ((x & 0xCCCCCCCC) >> 2)  | ((x & 0x33333333) << 2);
    x = ((x & 0xAAAAAAAA) >> 1)  | ((x & 0x55555555) << 1);
    return x;
}
```

**How it works:** Divide-and-conquer approach:
1. Swap 16-bit halves
2. Swap 8-bit halves within each 16-bit half
3. Swap 4-bit nibbles within each byte
4. Swap 2-bit pairs within each nibble
5. Swap adjacent bits

O(log n) operations — 5 steps for 32 bits.

**ARM has a dedicated instruction:** `RBIT` reverses bits in one cycle on Cortex-M3+. GCC: `__builtin_arm_rbit(x)`. But interviewers want to see you implement it.

