**Super-loop (bare-metal):**
```c
int main(void) {
    system_init();
    while (1) {
        poll_uart();
        read_sensors();
        update_display();
        check_buttons();
        process_commands();
    }
}
```

**RTOS (task-based):**
```c
int main(void) {
    system_init();
    xTaskCreate(uart_task, "UART", 256, NULL, 3, NULL);
    xTaskCreate(sensor_task, "SENSOR", 256, NULL, 2, NULL);
    xTaskCreate(display_task, "DISPLAY", 512, NULL, 1, NULL);
    vTaskStartScheduler(); // Never returns
}
```

**Comparison:**
| Factor | Super-loop | RTOS |
|--------|-----------|------|
| Complexity | Simple | More infrastructure |
| RAM overhead | None | Stack per task (256B-4KB each), kernel ~2-8KB |
| Timing | Non-deterministic (loop time varies) | Preemptive, priority-based |
| Blocking I/O | Can't block (stalls everything) | Tasks block independently |
| Debug | Easy (single flow) | Harder (concurrency bugs) |
| CPU sleep | Manual (sleep at end of loop) | Idle task handles it |
| Code modularity | Functions share one flow | Tasks are independent |

**When to stay bare-metal:**
- Simple devices (1-3 functions, no complex timing)
- Very constrained MCUs (<8KB RAM, <32KB flash)
- Hard real-time where you want full timing control
- Battery-powered devices with aggressive sleep (simpler sleep/wake)

**When to use an RTOS:**
- Multiple independent subsystems with different timing needs
- Need blocking I/O (wait for UART response, delay 100ms) without stalling everything
- Complex communication protocols (TCP/IP, USB, BLE)
- Team of developers working on different features
- 3+ tasks with different priorities

**The hybrid:** Many systems use interrupts + flags with super-loop for time-critical stuff, adding cooperative scheduling for background tasks. This gives you most RTOS benefits without the overhead.

**Rule of thumb:** If you find yourself writing state machines to avoid blocking in a super-loop, you want an RTOS. If `while(!ready)` spinlocks are creeping in, you NEED an RTOS.

