```c
void *my_memcpy(void *dst, const void *src, size_t n) {
    uint8_t *d = (uint8_t *)dst;
    const uint8_t *s = (const uint8_t *)src;
    while (n--) *d++ = *s++; // Always copies forward
    return dst;
}

void *my_memmove(void *dst, const void *src, size_t n) {
    uint8_t *d = (uint8_t *)dst;
    const uint8_t *s = (const uint8_t *)src;
    if (d < s) {
        while (n--) *d++ = *s++; // Forward copy
    } else {
        d += n; s += n;
        while (n--) *--d = *--s; // Backward copy
    }
    return dst;
}
```

**Why memcpy fails on overlap:** If `dst` is within `src`'s range and after it, forward copying overwrites source data before it's read.

**memmove** checks the direction and copies backward when needed, preserving the source data.

**Firmware context:** `memcpy` with `restrict` pointers lets the compiler vectorize/unroll. `memmove` can't be optimized as aggressively because of the overlap check. Use `memcpy` when you know buffers don't overlap (which is most of the time).

