questions.answer:
**The problem:** ISRs run with elevated priority. While an ISR is executing:
- Other (same or lower priority) interrupts are blocked
- Scheduling is suspended
- Long ISRs increase interrupt latency for the whole system

**The solution: top half / bottom half split**

```
[Hardware event]
       │
  TOP HALF (ISR)
  ─────────────
  • Acknowledge interrupt (clear HW flag)
  • Capture minimal state (e.g., read FIFO byte, timestamp)
  • Schedule bottom half
  • Return FAST (<1-5μs)
       │
  BOTTOM HALF (deferred, task context)
  ────────────────────────────────────
  • Do the real work
  • Can use blocking primitives (mutex, queue, sleep)
  • Runs at normal task priority
```

---

**Mechanism 1: RTOS Task + Semaphore**
Best for: general-purpose deferred work, moderate complexity
```c
static SemaphoreHandle_t work_sem;

void DMA_ISR(void) {
    clear_dma_irq();
    xSemaphoreGiveFromISR(work_sem, NULL); // Signal task
}

void dma_worker_task(void *arg) {
    while (1) {
        xSemaphoreTake(work_sem, portMAX_DELAY);
        process_dma_buffer(); // Safe to do complex work here
    }
}
```
- Pro: Simple, leverages RTOS scheduling
- Con: Task context switch overhead (~microseconds)

---

**Mechanism 2: Queue / Mailbox**
Best for: passing data with the notification
```c
static QueueHandle_t event_queue;

typedef struct { uint32_t timestamp; uint8_t byte; } Event;

void UART_RX_ISR(void) {
    Event e = { get_tick(), UART->DR };
    xQueueSendFromISR(event_queue, &e, NULL);
}

void uart_task(void *arg) {
    Event e;
    while (xQueueReceive(event_queue, &e, portMAX_DELAY))
        handle_uart_event(&e);
}
```
- Pro: Data travels with the notification, FIFO ordering
- Con: Queue overhead, item size must be fixed

---

**Mechanism 3: Volatile Flag / SPSC Ring**
Best for: baremetal (no RTOS), tight ISR→main-loop signaling
```c
static volatile bool event_pending = false;

void TIM_ISR(void) {
    capture_timestamp();
    event_pending = true; // Main loop polls this
}

int main(void) {
    while (1) {
        if (event_pending) {
            event_pending = false;
            process_event(); // Main loop context
        }
        // Other work...
    }
}
```
- Pro: Zero overhead, works without RTOS
- Con: Polling latency, volatile is not atomic for >1 bit of data, risk of double-event miss

---

**Mechanism 4: Tasklet / Softirq (Linux kernel)**
Best for: Linux driver development
- `request_threaded_irq()` splits handler into hard IRQ part and threaded part
- Threaded part runs as a kernel thread, can sleep
- Used in display drivers for frame processing after VBlank interrupt

---

**Synchronization rules for ISR↔task:**
- ISRs **cannot** use regular mutexes (they would sleep if contested)
- ISRs **can** use: spinlocks (briefly), RTOS ISR-safe APIs (`...FromISR`), atomic stores/flags
- On ARM bare-metal: disable IRQ for critical section in task side if needed
- On SMP: also need spinlock, not just IRQ disable

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <string.h>

#define HASH_SIZE 64

typedef struct Node {
    int key, value;
    struct Node *prev, *next;  // Doubly-linked list
    struct Node *hash_next;    // Hash chain
} Node;

typedef struct {
    Node  *hash[HASH_SIZE];  // Hash table: key → node
    Node  *head, *tail;      // Doubly-linked list (MRU at head, LRU at tail)
    int    capacity;
    int    size;
} LRUCache;

static int hash_key(int key) { return ((unsigned)key) % HASH_SIZE; }

LRUCache *lru_create(int capacity) {
    LRUCache *c = calloc(1, sizeof(*c));
    c->capacity = capacity;
    return c;
}

static void list_remove(LRUCache *c, Node *n) {
    if (n->prev) n->prev->next = n->next; else c->head = n->next;
    if (n->next) n->next->prev = n->prev; else c->tail = n->prev;
    n->prev = n->next = NULL;
}

static void list_push_front(LRUCache *c, Node *n) {
    n->prev = NULL;
    n->next = c->head;
    if (c->head) c->head->prev = n;
    c->head = n;
    if (!c->tail) c->tail = n;
}

int lru_get(LRUCache *c, int key) {
    int h = hash_key(key);
    for (Node *n = c->hash[h]; n; n = n->hash_next) {
        if (n->key == key) {
            // Move to front (most recently used)
            list_remove(c, n);
            list_push_front(c, n);
            return n->value;
        }
    }
    return -1; // Not found
}

void lru_put(LRUCache *c, int key, int value) {
    // Check if key exists
    int h = hash_key(key);
    for (Node *n = c->hash[h]; n; n = n->hash_next) {
        if (n->key == key) {
            n->value = value;
            list_remove(c, n);
            list_push_front(c, n);
            return;
        }
    }
    // Evict LRU if full
    if (c->size == c->capacity) {
        Node *lru = c->tail;
        list_remove(c, lru);
        // Remove from hash
        int lh = hash_key(lru->key);
        Node **pp = &c->hash[lh];
        while (*pp && *pp != lru) pp = &(*pp)->hash_next;
        if (*pp) *pp = lru->hash_next;
        free(lru);
        c->size--;
    }
    // Insert new node
    Node *n = calloc(1, sizeof(*n));
    n->key = key; n->value = value;
    list_push_front(c, n);
    n->hash_next = c->hash[h];
    c->hash[h] = n;
    c->size++;
}
```

**Why doubly-linked list + hash map:**
- Hash map gives O(1) lookup by key
- Doubly-linked list allows O(1) move-to-front and O(1) evict-tail
- Without the doubly-linked list, moving a node to front is O(n)

**Firmware context:** LRU caches appear in:
- Translation tables / address caches in memory subsystems
- Command/response caches in protocol handlers
- Sensor data caches (return last N readings quickly)

