questions.answer:
**Vtable overhead breakdown:**

```
Per-class cost (in .rodata / flash):
  N virtual functions × sizeof(void*) bytes
  e.g., 5 virtual functions on Cortex-M32 = 5 × 4 = 20 bytes in flash

Per-object cost:
  vptr (vtable pointer): 4 bytes on 32-bit MCU
  Added to EVERY object — even when runtime poly is never used

Per-call cost (Cortex-M4, optimized):
  LDR  r3, [r0]          ; load vptr from object (possible D-cache miss)
  LDR  r3, [r3, #offset] ; load function pointer from vtable
  BLX  r3                ; indirect branch (branch predictor often misses)
  Approximate: 3–10 cycles + possible 5–15 cycle branch predictor miss

Direct call cost:
  BL   function           ; 1–3 cycles, always predicted, inlineable
```

**When virtual overhead matters:**
- Tight loops calling virtual methods (ADC sample processing, codec inner loop)
- Small MCUs (<16KB flash) where vtable adds significant percentage of code size
- Small objects where the 4-byte vptr is >25% of object size
- Deep call chains where vtable misses cascade

**When virtual is fine:**
- Initialization paths and state machine transitions (not in tight loops)
- When you actually need runtime polymorphism (plugin architecture)
- Large objects where 4-byte vptr is negligible overhead

---

**Alternative 1: CRTP (static polymorphism)**
```cpp
template<typename Derived>
class Sensor {
public:
    float read() { return static_cast<Derived*>(this)->read_impl(); }
};

class TemperatureSensor : public Sensor<TemperatureSensor> {
    float read_impl() { return adc_to_celsius(ADC1->DR); }
};

template<typename S>
void log_sensor(Sensor<S>& s) { printf("%.2f\n", s.read()); }
// read() is fully inlined — zero call overhead
```
✅ Zero overhead, inlineable
❌ Type fixed at compile time — can't store mixed `Sensor*` in an array

---

**Alternative 2: std::variant + std::visit**
```cpp
#include <variant>
using SensorVariant = std::variant<TempSensor, PressureSensor, HumiditySensor>;

float read_sensor(SensorVariant& s) {
    // Compiler generates a jump table (not vtable) — efficient
    return std::visit([](auto& sensor) { return sensor.read(); }, s);
}

// Store mixed types in contiguous array — cache-friendly
std::array<SensorVariant, 8> sensors;
```
✅ Runtime polymorphism without heap, no virtual overhead
✅ Exhaustive — compiler errors if a type is unhandled
❌ Object size = max(all variant sizes) — wastes memory for small types
❌ All types must be known at compile time

---

**Alternative 3: Function pointer tables (C-style, explicit)**
```cpp
struct SensorOps {
    float (*read)(void* ctx);
    void  (*calibrate)(void* ctx);
};

struct SensorInst {
    const SensorOps* ops;  // Points to ops table in flash
    void*            ctx;  // Driver-specific state
};

float sensor_read(SensorInst* s) { return s->ops->read(s->ctx); }
```
✅ Explicit, portable (C and C++), debugger-friendly
✅ Ops table can be in flash (`const`)
❌ No type safety, boilerplate for each operation

---

**Decision flowchart:**
```
Need runtime type selection? ─No─→ CRTP (zero cost)
        │Yes
        ↓
All types known at compile time? ─Yes─→ std::variant (type-safe, exhaustive)
        │No
        ↓
C compatibility needed? ─Yes─→ Function pointer table
        │No
        ↓
→ Virtual (runtime flexibility, familiar pattern)
```

```cpp
#include <cstddef>
#include <cstdint>
#include <new>
#include <cassert>

// Fixed-size object pool — O(1) alloc/free, zero fragmentation
template<typename T, size_t N>
class ObjectPool {
public:
    static_assert(N > 0, "Pool must have at least 1 slot");
    static_assert(sizeof(T) >= sizeof(uint32_t), "T too small for free-list");

    ObjectPool() {
        // Build intrusive free list: each free slot holds index of next free slot
        for (size_t i = 0; i < N - 1; ++i)
            free_list(i) = static_cast<uint32_t>(i + 1);
        free_list(N - 1) = INVALID;
        free_head_  = 0;
        free_count_ = N;
    }

    // Allocate and construct — O(1)
    template<typename... Args>
    T* alloc(Args&&... args) {
        if (free_head_ == INVALID) return nullptr;  // Pool exhausted

        size_t idx  = free_head_;
        free_head_  = free_list(idx);
        --free_count_;

        // Placement new: construct T in pre-allocated, aligned storage
        return new (slot_ptr(idx)) T(std::forward<Args>(args)...);
    }

    // Destroy and return to pool — O(1)
    void free(T* obj) {
        assert(obj != nullptr && owns(obj));
        obj->~T();  // Must explicitly call destructor with placement new

        size_t idx    = slot_index(obj);
        free_list(idx) = free_head_;
        free_head_    = static_cast<uint32_t>(idx);
        ++free_count_;
    }

    size_t free_count() const { return free_count_; }
    size_t capacity()   const { return N; }

private:
    static constexpr uint32_t INVALID = UINT32_MAX;

    // Each slot: aligned storage large enough for T
    struct alignas(T) Slot { uint8_t bytes[sizeof(T)]; };
    Slot slots_[N];
    uint32_t free_head_  = INVALID;
    size_t   free_count_ = 0;

    T*     slot_ptr(size_t i)   { return reinterpret_cast<T*>(&slots_[i]); }
    size_t slot_index(T* obj)   { return reinterpret_cast<Slot*>(obj) - slots_; }
    bool   owns(T* obj)         { auto* s = reinterpret_cast<Slot*>(obj); return s >= slots_ && s < slots_ + N; }

    // Intrusive free list stored IN the free slot
    uint32_t& free_list(size_t i) { return *reinterpret_cast<uint32_t*>(&slots_[i]); }
};
```

**Why avoid the default heap in embedded:**
1. **Fragmentation** — `malloc`/`free` over time create holes; eventually a large allocation fails with enough total free memory
2. **Non-deterministic timing** — `malloc` time varies; ISRs and real-time tasks need bounded execution time
3. **No early warning** — heap exhaustion discovered at runtime, deep in a call stack
4. **Thread safety overhead** — default heap requires a lock; pool allocators can be lock-free

**Pool allocator properties:**
- **O(1) allocation and deallocation** — just pop/push the free list
- **Zero fragmentation** — all allocations are the same size
- **Bounded size** — exhaustion detected immediately, not after corrupting state
- **Cache-friendly** — objects are contiguous in memory
- **Placement new** — no virtual `operator new` overhead; objects live in the pool's static array

