questions.answer:
**What a firmware image signature covers:**

```
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Image Header (hashed but describes the image)       │
│  Magic bytes, version, image size                    │
│  Signing algorithm ID, anti-rollback security counter│
├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  Image Body (code + rodata + vectors)                │
│  Everything that executes                            │
├──────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  TLV Trailer                                         │
│  SHA-256 hash of image body                          │
│  ECDSA P-256 signature over the hash                 │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

**Build-time signing:**
```bash
# MCUboot imgtool signs during build
imgtool sign \
    --key keys/firmware_signing_key.pem \
    --header-size 0x200 \
    --version 1.2.0+3 \    # +3 is the security counter (anti-rollback)
    --slot-size 0x60000 \
    firmware.bin firmware_signed.bin
```

**Bootloader verification pseudocode:**
```c
typedef enum {
    VERIFY_OK, VERIFY_BAD_MAGIC, VERIFY_BAD_HASH,
    VERIFY_BAD_SIG, VERIFY_ROLLBACK
} VerifyResult;

// Public key embedded in bootloader — itself verified by RoT
static const uint8_t PUBKEY[64] = { /* EC P-256 X,Y coords */ };

VerifyResult verify_image(const uint8_t* image, size_t len,
                          const ImageHeader* hdr) {
    // 1. Sanity checks
    if (hdr->magic != FIRMWARE_MAGIC) return VERIFY_BAD_MAGIC;

    // 2. Anti-rollback BEFORE crypto (fast, cheap)
    if (hdr->security_counter < otp_read_min_version())
        return VERIFY_ROLLBACK;

    // 3. Compute SHA-256 hash
    uint8_t computed[32];
    sha256(image, len, computed);

    // 4. Constant-time hash comparison (CRITICAL!)
    const uint8_t* stored = tlv_find(image, TLV_SHA256);
    if (!stored || !mem_eq_ct(computed, stored, 32))
        return VERIFY_BAD_HASH;

    // 5. Verify ECDSA signature over the hash
    const uint8_t* sig = tlv_find(image, TLV_ECDSA256);
    if (!sig || !ecdsa_p256_verify(computed, sig, PUBKEY))
        return VERIFY_BAD_SIG;

    return VERIFY_OK;
}

// CRITICAL: constant-time comparison — timing leak enables oracle attacks
bool mem_eq_ct(const uint8_t* a, const uint8_t* b, size_t n) {
    uint8_t diff = 0;
    for (size_t i = 0; i < n; i++) diff |= a[i] ^ b[i];
    return diff == 0;  // Single check, no early exit
}
```

**ECDSA P-256 vs RSA-2048 for embedded:**

| | ECDSA P-256 | RSA-2048 |
|---|---|---|
| Public key size | 64 bytes | 256+ bytes |
| Signature size | 64 bytes | 256 bytes |
| Verification time @ 168MHz | ~300ms | ~1500ms |
| Library flash | ~10KB (mbedTLS) | ~15KB |
| Security level | 128-bit equivalent | 112-bit equivalent |
| **Recommendation** | Preferred for embedded | Too slow and large |

**Anti-rollback protection:**
```
Problem: Attacker re-flashes an old but valid-signature firmware that has
         a known vulnerability. Signature check passes!

Solution: Monotonic OTP/eFUSE counter (can only increment, never decrement)
  Image header: security_counter = 4
  OTP stores:   min_version = 4

  On first successful boot of new image:
    burn OTP counter to max(current, image_counter)
  Future images with counter < 4: REJECTED at step 2
```

**Why AES-GCM over AES-CBC:**

AES-CBC provides confidentiality only — it doesn't detect tampering. An attacker can flip bits in the ciphertext and cause controlled, predictable changes in the plaintext (CBC bit-flip attack, padding oracle).

AES-GCM is **AEAD** (Authenticated Encryption with Associated Data):
- **Confidentiality**: ciphertext unreadable without the key
- **Integrity + Authenticity**: 128-bit GCM tag detects ANY tampering
- **Associated data**: authenticate unencrypted headers along with ciphertext

```
AES-GCM wire format:
┌─────────┬──────────────────────────┬──────────┐
│  Nonce  │       Ciphertext         │  GCM Tag │
│  12 B   │  len(plaintext) bytes    │   16 B   │
└─────────┴──────────────────────────┴──────────┘
          Both fields verified by recipient
```

**Correct AES-128-GCM usage (mbedTLS):**

```c
#include "mbedtls/gcm.h"

#define KEY_LEN   16  // AES-128
#define NONCE_LEN 12  // GCM standard: 96-bit nonce
#define TAG_LEN   16  // Full 128-bit authentication tag

int encrypt_packet(const uint8_t key[KEY_LEN],
                   const uint8_t* aad, size_t aad_len,
                   const uint8_t* plain, size_t plain_len,
                   uint8_t* nonce_out, uint8_t* cipher_out,
                   uint8_t* tag_out) {
    mbedtls_gcm_context ctx;
    mbedtls_gcm_init(&ctx);

    // Step 1: Set key
    int ret = mbedtls_gcm_setkey(&ctx, MBEDTLS_CIPHER_ID_AES,
                                 key, KEY_LEN * 8);
    if (ret != 0) goto done;

    // Step 2: Generate RANDOM nonce — NEVER reuse with same key!
    ret = hardware_rng_generate(nonce_out, NONCE_LEN);
    if (ret != 0) goto done;

    // Step 3: Encrypt + generate authentication tag
    ret = mbedtls_gcm_crypt_and_tag(
        &ctx, MBEDTLS_GCM_ENCRYPT, plain_len,
        nonce_out, NONCE_LEN,   // Nonce
        aad, aad_len,           // Additional authenticated data
        plain, cipher_out,      // Plaintext in, ciphertext out
        TAG_LEN, tag_out        // Auth tag output
    );

done:
    mbedtls_gcm_free(&ctx);
    return ret;
}

int decrypt_packet(const uint8_t key[KEY_LEN],
                   const uint8_t* aad, size_t aad_len,
                   const uint8_t* nonce,
                   const uint8_t* cipher, size_t cipher_len,
                   const uint8_t* tag,
                   uint8_t* plain_out) {
    mbedtls_gcm_context ctx;
    mbedtls_gcm_init(&ctx);
    mbedtls_gcm_setkey(&ctx, MBEDTLS_CIPHER_ID_AES, key, KEY_LEN * 8);

    // Decrypt AND verify tag simultaneously
    // Returns MBEDTLS_ERR_GCM_AUTH_FAILED if tampered or wrong key
    int ret = mbedtls_gcm_auth_decrypt(
        &ctx, cipher_len,
        nonce, NONCE_LEN,
        aad, aad_len,
        tag, TAG_LEN,      // Expected tag — verification happens here
        cipher, plain_out  // DO NOT act on plain_out if ret != 0!
    );

    mbedtls_gcm_free(&ctx);
    return ret;
}
```

**Critical rules:**

**1. NEVER reuse a nonce with the same key:**
```
If (nonce, key) is used twice → catastrophic
Attacker XORs two ciphertexts → keystream cancels → XOR of plaintexts exposed
→ Both messages compromised regardless of key strength

Solutions:
  a) 96-bit random nonce (collision probability < 2^-32 for <2^32 messages)
  b) Counter-based nonce: 32-bit sequence number padded to 96 bits
  c) Per-session key derivation (new key = new nonce space)
```

**2. Key storage — keys must NOT be:**
- In flash (readable with JTAG, extractable from firmware binary)
- In plaintext SRAM (readable via debug port or memory dump)

**Keys SHOULD be in:**
- OTP/eFUSE burned during manufacturing
- Hardware Security Element (SE050, ATECC608B)
- TrustZone Secure World memory
- Derived per-session from a root key via HKDF

**3. Always include sequence numbers in AAD (anti-replay):**
```c
uint8_t aad[8];
memcpy(aad, &seq_num, 4);    // Prevents replaying old valid packets
memcpy(aad + 4, &dev_id, 4);
```

**Flash layout for A/B OTA:**
```
512KB Flash:
┌──────────┬──────────────┬──────────────┬────────────────┐
│  BL      │  Slot A      │  Slot B      │  Config/Keys   │
│  64KB    │  200KB       │  200KB       │  48KB          │
│ (RDP2)   │ (active fw)  │ (new fw)     │ (certs, NVS)   │
└──────────┴──────────────┴──────────────┴────────────────┘
```

**Phase 1: Secure transport (download)**
```c
// TLS 1.3 with certificate pinning — reject any cert not matching
// your specific update server, not just 'any valid CA'
bool verify_server_cert(const uint8_t* cert, size_t len) {
    uint8_t cert_hash[32];
    sha256(cert, len, cert_hash);
    return mem_eq_ct(cert_hash, PINNED_CERT_HASH, 32);
}

// Chunk-based download to fit in RAM
#define CHUNK_SIZE 4096
bool download_chunk(uint32_t offset, uint8_t* buf, size_t* len) {
    return https_get_range(OTA_URL, offset, CHUNK_SIZE, buf, len);
}
```

**Phase 2: Stream to inactive slot (Slot B)**
```c
bool ota_begin(size_t total_size, const uint8_t sha256_expected[32]) {
    if (total_size > SLOT_SIZE) return false;
    flash_erase(SLOT_B_START, SLOT_B_SIZE);       // Erase before write
    memcpy(ota_ctx.expected_hash, sha256_expected, 32);
    ota_ctx.written = 0;
    sha256_init(&ota_ctx.hash_state);
    return true;
}

bool ota_write_chunk(const uint8_t* data, size_t len) {
    flash_write(SLOT_B_START + ota_ctx.written, data, len);
    sha256_update(&ota_ctx.hash_state, data, len); // Hash incrementally
    ota_ctx.written += len;
    return true;
}
```

**Phase 3: Verify BEFORE committing to swap**
```c
bool ota_finalize(void) {
    // 1. Size sanity
    if (ota_ctx.written != ota_ctx.total_size) return false;

    // 2. Integrity — SHA-256 hash
    uint8_t computed[32];
    sha256_final(&ota_ctx.hash_state, computed);
    if (!mem_eq_ct(computed, ota_ctx.expected_hash, 32)) return false;

    // 3. Authenticity — ECDSA signature via MCUboot
    if (!mcuboot_verify_slot(SLOT_B)) return false;

    // 4. Anti-rollback version check
    uint32_t new_ver = mcuboot_get_security_counter(SLOT_B);
    if (new_ver < otp_read_min_version()) return false;

    // 5. Mark upgrade pending — atomic write to swap state area
    mcuboot_set_upgrade_pending();
    return true;
}
```

**Phase 4: Atomic swap in bootloader (MCUboot)**
```
Boot sequence:
  BL detects Slot B marked 'upgrade pending'
  BL re-verifies Slot B signature (defense in depth)
  BL swaps Slot B -> Slot A (page-by-page with rollback state)
  BL marks Slot A 'needs confirmation'
  BL boots Slot A (new firmware)

Application must call mcuboot_confirm_upgrade() within timeout:
  Confirmed -> permanent, burn OTP counter if version increased
  Not confirmed (crash) -> BL reverts to Slot B on next boot
```

**Phase 5: Application self-test and confirmation**
```c
void app_startup_complete(void) {
    if (mcuboot_pending_confirmation()) {
        // Run self-tests
        if (all_subsystems_healthy() && network_reachable()) {
            mcuboot_confirm_upgrade();
            otp_update_min_version(new_security_counter);
        }
        // If not confirmed: watchdog expires -> revert
    }
}
```

**Security checklist:**
| Threat | Mitigation |
|---|---|
| Network MITM | TLS 1.3 + certificate pinning |
| Rogue firmware | ECDSA P-256 code signing |
| Replay old update | Anti-rollback OTP counter |
| Power loss during write | A/B swap + MCUboot state machine |
| Corrupt image | SHA-256 hash before swap |
| Bricking device | Rollback if not confirmed |

**What are side-channel attacks?**

Side-channel attacks extract secret information from physical measurements rather than breaking the algorithm mathematically:
- **Timing** — how long operations take
- **Power consumption** — how much current the chip draws (SPA, DPA)
- **Electromagnetic** — EM radiation from switching

These bypass cryptographic strength entirely — AES-128 is unbreakable mathematically but leaks the key through physical implementation.

---

**Timing attack — vulnerable comparison:**

```c
// VULNERABLE: early exit leaks information about how many bytes matched
bool compare_mac(const uint8_t* computed, const uint8_t* received,
                 size_t len) {
    for (size_t i = 0; i < len; i++) {
        if (computed[i] != received[i])
            return false;  // Returns earlier for earlier mismatch!
    }
    return true;
}

// Attack:
// Measure time for mac[0] = 0x00 vs 0x01 vs ... vs 0xFF
// The byte that takes longer before returning = correct byte
// For 16-byte MAC with 256 values: 256 * 16 = 4096 guesses
// vs 256^16 = 2^128 brute force — 10^35 times faster
```

**Constant-time fix:**

```c
// SECURE: always takes identical time regardless of where mismatch is
bool compare_mac_ct(const uint8_t* a, const uint8_t* b, size_t len) {
    uint8_t diff = 0;
    for (size_t i = 0; i < len; i++) {
        diff |= a[i] ^ b[i];  // Accumulate all differences, no early exit
    }
    return diff == 0;  // Single final check
}

// WARNING: naive volatile may not be enough — compiler may still optimize
// Use vetted library functions:
// OpenSSL: CRYPTO_memcmp()
// mbedTLS: mbedtls_ct_memcmp()
// These are verified at assembly level to be constant-time

// Also constant-time: use this pattern for checking flags
// WRONG:
if (valid) { do_operation(); }

// RIGHT (when valid is secret):
// Use bitmask: operation runs always, result is masked
uint32_t mask = -(uint32_t)valid;  // 0xFFFFFFFF if valid, 0x00000000 if not
result = (operation_result & mask) | (safe_default & ~mask);
```

---

**Simple Power Analysis (SPA):**
```
Attacker watches oscilloscope during RSA decryption:
  Square-and-multiply algorithm:
    Bit = 0: square only       -> short, low-power pattern
    Bit = 1: square + multiply -> longer, higher-power pattern
  Each bit of private key is directly visible as a power pattern
  Full key extracted from a SINGLE trace

Fix: square-and-always-multiply
  ALWAYS execute multiply, even for bit = 0 (discard result)
  Both branches look identical in power trace
```

**Differential Power Analysis (DPA) — Paul Kocher, 1999:**
```
1. Collect N power traces (N ~ 1000-10000) encrypting known plaintexts
2. Guess one AES key byte (256 possible values)
3. For each guess, compute predicted SubBytes output bit
4. Split traces into two groups by that predicted bit
5. Average each group separately and subtract:
   Correct guess -> averaging reinforces the signal (real bit affects power)
   Wrong guess   -> averaging cancels out (incorrect prediction = noise)
6. Repeat for each byte -> full AES-128 key in minutes from one device
```

**DPA countermeasures:**

| Countermeasure | Mechanism | Effectiveness |
|---|---|---|
| Masking | XOR intermediate values with random mask; re-mask before output | High — breaks correlation |
| Randomized execution order | Shuffle SubBytes order | Medium — raises traces needed |
| Hardware noise injection | Random delays, clock jitter | Low-medium |
| Hardware AES with built-in masking | STM32 AES with countermeasures | High |
| Dedicated HSM (ATECC608B, SE050) | DPA-hardened hardware | Very high |
| Dual-rail logic | Both 0 and 1 driven simultaneously | Very high (special cell library) |

**Masked AES pseudocode:**
```c
// Masking: hide intermediate value with random mask r
// SubBytes(state XOR mask) != SubBytes(state) XOR SubBytes(mask)
// So we precompute a masked S-box: MaskedSBox[x XOR r] = SBox[x] XOR r'
uint8_t masked_sbox[256];
for (int i = 0; i < 256; i++)
    masked_sbox[i ^ mask_in] = sbox[i] ^ mask_out;
// Now SubBytes using masked_sbox leaks no information about the key byte
```

