questions.answer:
**What is fault injection?**

Fault injection deliberately induces transient hardware faults during execution — causing the CPU to skip instructions, corrupt data, or take wrong branches. Unlike side-channel attacks (passive), fault injection is **active** — the attacker changes device behavior.

---

**Attack techniques:**

**Voltage glitching:**
```
Normal VCC: 3.3V (stable)
Attack: drop VCC to ~2.1V for 5-50 nanoseconds at a precise moment

Effect:
  Setup/hold time violations in flip-flops
  Single bit flips in pipeline registers
  Most commonly: skip 1-2 instructions

Equipment: $200-500 ChipWhisperer or DIY MOSFET circuit
Success rate: 1-10% per attempt; automated at ~1000 attempts/second
```

**Clock glitching:**
```
Normal clock: clean 168MHz
Attack: inject extra clock edge or stretch/shrink one cycle

Effect: CPU executes next instruction with setup time violation
  Combinational logic outputs wrong value
  Register latches garbage
  Common target: branch instructions, comparison results
```

---

**Target: signature verification bypass**
```c
// VULNERABLE to single-instruction skip:
bool check_firmware(const uint8_t* image, size_t len) {
    bool result = ecdsa_verify(image, len, PUBLIC_KEY);
    if (!result) {   // <- SKIP this instruction with fault injection
        return false;
    }
    return true;   // <- Attacker lands here without valid signature
}

// Even more vulnerable:
if (ecdsa_verify(image, len, key))  // <- BNE glitched to BEQ
    boot_firmware();
```

---

**Countermeasure 1: Multi-byte magic result codes**
```c
// Single-bit result is easy to flip; multi-byte patterns are not
#define VERIFY_OK   0xA5C36E91u  // Random non-trivial value
#define VERIFY_FAIL 0x5A3C916Eu  // Bitwise complement of OK

uint32_t check_firmware(const uint8_t* image, size_t len) {
    uint32_t result = VERIFY_FAIL;  // Start as FAIL — explicit

    if (ecdsa_verify(image, len, PUBLIC_KEY)) {
        result = VERIFY_OK;
    }

    // Attacker must flip the variable AND survive this second check
    if (result != VERIFY_OK) {
        return VERIFY_FAIL;
    }
    return result;
}

// Caller also validates:
uint32_t v = check_firmware(image, len);
if (v != VERIFY_OK) {
    // Log + halt — never continue past a failed check
    log_security_event(VERIFY_FAILED);
    while (1);  // Or NVIC_SystemReset()
}
```

**Countermeasure 2: Verify twice with random delay**
```c
bool secure_verify(const uint8_t* image, size_t len) {
    bool r1 = ecdsa_verify(image, len, PUBLIC_KEY);

    // Random delay: precise timing needed for glitch -> harder to synchronize
    volatile uint32_t delay = 10000 + (hardware_rng() & 0xFFFF);
    while (delay--) __asm__("nop");

    bool r2 = ecdsa_verify(image, len, PUBLIC_KEY);

    // Disagreement = fault injection detected
    if (r1 != r2) {
        log_security_event(FAULT_INJECTION_SUSPECTED);
        NVIC_SystemReset();
    }
    return r1 && r2;
}
```

**Countermeasure 3: Redundant shadow variables**
```c
typedef struct {
    uint32_t val;        // Primary value
    uint32_t shadow;     // Redundant copy
    uint32_t complement; // Bitwise complement
} RedundantFlag;

// A single fault can't consistently corrupt all three
bool check_redundant(const RedundantFlag* f) {
    return (f->val == VERIFY_OK)
        && (f->shadow == VERIFY_OK)
        && (f->complement == ~VERIFY_OK)
        && (f->val == f->shadow);
}
```

**Hardware countermeasures:**

| Countermeasure | Effect |
|---|---|
| Voltage monitor (BOD) | Detect glitch → immediate reset |
| Clock monitor | Detect extra/missing clock edge → reset |
| Active mesh (tamper) | Physical tamper → erase keys |
| Memory ECC | Detect single-bit errors in SRAM/flash |
| Random delay injection | Precise timing required → harder to synchronize |
| Dedicated HSM (SE050, STSAFE) | Fault-hardened hardware, certified against FI |

```c
// STM32: Enable brown-out reset at ~2.7V
// Prevents attacker from dropping voltage just enough to cause faults
// without triggering a reset
HAL_PWREx_EnableBOR(PWR_BOR_LEVEL_4);
```

**TrustZone for Cortex-M (ARMv8-M):**

TrustZone creates two hardware-isolated worlds on a single CPU core. Unlike a hypervisor (which virtualizes in time), TrustZone partitions the system in space — each world has separate register banks, stack pointers, and assigned memory regions.

```
Single ARM Cortex-M33 core:
┌────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────┐
│   SECURE WORLD (S)     │   NON-SECURE WORLD (NS)    │
│                        │                            │
│ • Crypto keys          │ • Application code         │
│ • Secure boot code     │ • Comms stack              │
│ • Attestation          │ • Sensor processing        │
│ • Secure storage       │ • UI / display             │
│ • Trusted services     │ • Third-party libraries    │
│                        │                            │
│ Cannot be accessed     │ Cannot access Secure       │
│ from NS world          │ memory even with bug/ROP   │
└────────────────────────┴────────────────────────────┘
```

---

**Security Attribution Unit (SAU):**

The SAU assigns each memory region to one of three security states:
```c
// Configure SAU regions
void sau_configure(void) {
    SAU->CTRL = 0;  // Disable SAU during config

    // Region 0: Non-Secure flash (NS application code)
    SAU->RNR  = 0;
    SAU->RBAR = 0x00200000;           // NS flash start
    SAU->RLAR = 0x003FFFE0 | SAU_RLAR_ENABLE_Msk;

    // Region 1: Non-Secure Callable (NSC) — gateway functions
    SAU->RNR  = 1;
    SAU->RBAR = 0x0001F000;           // NSC region
    SAU->RLAR = 0x0001FFFE | SAU_RLAR_ENABLE_Msk | SAU_RLAR_NSC_Msk;

    // Region 2: Non-Secure SRAM
    SAU->RNR  = 2;
    SAU->RBAR = 0x20020000;
    SAU->RLAR = 0x2003FFFE | SAU_RLAR_ENABLE_Msk;

    // Region 3: Non-Secure peripherals
    SAU->RNR  = 3;
    SAU->RBAR = 0x40040000;
    SAU->RLAR = 0x4007FFFE | SAU_RLAR_ENABLE_Msk;

    SAU->CTRL = SAU_CTRL_ENABLE_Msk;  // Enable SAU
    // All unmarked regions default to Secure
}
```

**Three security states:**
- **Secure (S):** Private to Secure World — keys, crypto routines
- **Non-Secure Callable (NSC):** NS can call functions here via `BLXNS` instruction
- **Non-Secure (NS):** Application code and data

---

**How NS calls S services (veneer functions):**

```c
// Secure World: defines a gateway (veneer) in the NSC region
// The __attribute__((cmse_nonsecure_entry)) marks this as callable from NS
__attribute__((cmse_nonsecure_entry))
int32_t s_crypto_sign(const uint8_t* data, size_t len,
                      uint8_t* sig_out) {
    // Validate pointers — CRITICAL! NS must not pass S pointers
    if (cmse_check_pointed_object(data, CMSE_MPU_READ) == NULL)
        return -1;
    if (cmse_check_pointed_object(sig_out, CMSE_MPU_READWRITE) == NULL)
        return -1;

    // Access keys from Secure memory (NS can NEVER reach these)
    const uint8_t* key = secure_key_store_get_signing_key();
    return ecdsa_p256_sign(data, len, key, sig_out);
    // On return: TZ clears S registers automatically before NS resumes
}

// Non-Secure World: calls via function pointer to NSC region
// Compiler generates BLXNS instruction (Non-Secure branch)
extern int32_t s_crypto_sign(const uint8_t*, size_t, uint8_t*);

void app_sign_telemetry(const TelemetryPacket* pkt, uint8_t* sig) {
    // This call crosses the Secure boundary safely
    int32_t ret = s_crypto_sign(pkt->data, pkt->len, sig);
    if (ret != 0) { handle_error(); }
}
```

**Register clearing on world transition:**
When NS calls into S via `BLXNS`, the CPU automatically:
1. Saves the return address (with LSB=0 to mark non-secure return)
2. Pushes an integrity signature to prevent tampering
3. Clears caller-saved registers (r0-r3, r12, lr) — prevents NS data leaking into S

On return from S to NS:
1. Clears caller-saved registers — prevents S secrets leaking into NS
2. Validates the integrity signature

---

**TF-M (Trusted Firmware-M) architecture:**

```
Secure World (TF-M):
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  Secure Partition Manager (SPM)                     │
│  • Routes IPC calls between partitions              │
│  • Enforces partition isolation (S-MPU)             │
│  • Manages secure interrupt handling                │
│                                                     │
│  ┌──────────────┐  ┌──────────────────────────┐    │
│  │ Crypto SP    │  │ Protected Storage SP      │    │
│  │ (PSA Crypto) │  │ (NV key-value store,      │    │
│  │ AES, SHA,    │  │  authenticated with AEAD) │    │
│  │ ECDSA, RNG   │  │                           │    │
│  └──────────────┘  └──────────────────────────┘    │
│                                                     │
│  ┌──────────────┐  ┌──────────────────────────┐    │
│  │ Attestation  │  │ Initial Attestation Token │    │
│  │ (EAT/CBOR)   │  │ (signed device identity)  │    │
│  └──────────────┘  └──────────────────────────┘    │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

Non-Secure World:
  Uses PSA API (psa_crypto_init, psa_sign_hash, ...)
  Calls route through NSC veneer -> SPM -> target partition
```

**PSA API call from NS:**
```c
// NS application uses standardized PSA Crypto API
// Implementation lives in TF-M Secure Partition
#include "psa/crypto.h"

void sign_with_device_key(const uint8_t* msg, size_t len,
                          uint8_t* sig, size_t* sig_len) {
    psa_key_handle_t key;       // Handle, not the actual key
    // Key material NEVER leaves the Secure World
    psa_open_key(DEVICE_SIGNING_KEY_ID, &key);
    psa_sign_message(key, PSA_ALG_ECDSA(PSA_ALG_SHA_256),
                     msg, len, sig, 72, sig_len);
    psa_close_key(key);
}
```

**When to use TrustZone vs MPU-only:**
- MPU: bugs caught, privilege separation enforced, suitable for Cortex-M3/M4/M7
- TrustZone: need to run untrusted/downloadable code, defense/banking/medical requirements, need proven NS-can-never-reach-S isolation, available on Cortex-M23/M33+

**Inheritance access rules:**

```
Base member    public inh.    protected inh.    private inh.
─────────────  ────────────   ───────────────   ─────────────
public    →    public         protected         private
protected →    protected      protected         private
private   →    inaccessible   inaccessible      inaccessible
```

**`public` inheritance** (most common): Models "is-a" relationship. `Derived` IS A `Base`. External code sees the full public interface.
```cpp
class UartDriver : public PeripheralDriver { ... };
// UartDriver IS A PeripheralDriver — can be used wherever PeripheralDriver expected
```

**`protected` inheritance** (rare): Derived and its children can use Base's public interface, but external code cannot. Base's public members become protected.

**`private` inheritance** (occasionally useful): Models "implemented-in-terms-of." External code can't see the base at all. No implicit conversion to Base*.
```cpp
class Logger : private RingBuffer { ... };
// Logger USES a RingBuffer internally, but isn't one publicly
```

**When to prefer composition over inheritance:**
```cpp
// BAD — SensorManager is NOT a Timer
class SensorManager : public Timer { ... };

// GOOD — SensorManager HAS a Timer
class SensorManager {
    Timer sampleTimer;
    AdcDriver adc;
    Filter filter;
public:
    void poll() {
        if (sampleTimer.expired()) {
            auto reading = adc.read();
            filter.update(reading);
        }
    }
};
```

**Rule of thumb for embedded:** Prefer composition. It's more flexible, avoids vtable overhead, and makes dependencies explicit. Use public inheritance only when you genuinely need polymorphism (e.g., a driver interface that multiple implementations share).

