questions.answer:
**Abstract class:** A class with at least one **pure virtual function** (`= 0`). Cannot be instantiated directly.

```cpp
class Sensor {
public:
    virtual int read() = 0;          // pure virtual — MUST be overridden
    virtual void calibrate() = 0;    // pure virtual
    void logReading() {              // non-virtual — shared implementation OK
        printf("Reading: %d\n", read());
    }
    virtual ~Sensor() = default;
};

Sensor s;           // ERROR: cannot instantiate abstract class
Sensor* sp;         // OK: can have pointers/references
```

**Yes, abstract classes can have:**
- Non-virtual member functions (shared behavior)
- Data members (shared state)
- Constructors (called by derived class constructors)
- Even **definitions** for pure virtual functions (callable via `Base::method()`)

**Interface Segregation Principle (ISP):**
"No client should be forced to depend on methods it does not use."

**Bad — fat interface:**
```cpp
class IPeripheral {
public:
    virtual bool init() = 0;
    virtual int read() = 0;
    virtual int write(uint8_t) = 0;
    virtual void setPower(int mode) = 0;
    virtual void enableDma() = 0;
    virtual int dmaTransfer(void*, size_t) = 0;
    virtual void enableInterrupt() = 0;
    virtual ~IPeripheral() = default;
};
// A simple GPIO class must implement DMA and interrupt methods it doesn't need!
```

**Good — segregated interfaces:**
```cpp
class IReadable { public: virtual int read() = 0; virtual ~IReadable() = default; };
class IWritable { public: virtual int write(uint8_t) = 0; virtual ~IWritable() = default; };
class IDmaCapable { public: virtual int dmaTransfer(void*, size_t) = 0; virtual ~IDmaCapable() = default; };
class IPowerManaged { public: virtual void setPower(int) = 0; virtual ~IPowerManaged() = default; };

// ADC only implements what it needs
class AdcDriver : public IReadable, public IPowerManaged { ... };

// DMA UART implements more
class DmaUart : public IReadable, public IWritable, public IDmaCapable { ... };
```

**Why ISP matters in firmware:**
- Smaller interfaces = smaller vtables = less flash
- Mock testing is easier (implement one small interface, not a god-object)
- Drivers only depend on capabilities they actually use
- New peripherals don't break existing code

**Scenario 1 — Slicing in assignment:**
```cpp
Derived d;
Base b = d;  // SLICED — only Base portion copied, vptr is Base's
b.identify(); // Calls Base::identify(), not Derived::identify()
// Fix: use pointer or reference
Base& ref = d;
ref.identify(); // Correctly calls Derived::identify()
```

**Scenario 2 — Slicing in function parameter:**
```cpp
void process(Base b) { b.identify(); }  // Receives a COPY — sliced!
process(d);  // Calls Base::identify()
// Fix: pass by reference or pointer
void process(Base& b) { b.identify(); }  // No copy, no slice
```

**Scenario 3 — Slicing in a container:**
```cpp
std::vector<Base> devices;  // Stores Base VALUES — any Derived pushed in gets sliced
devices.push_back(Derived());  // Sliced to Base
// Fix: store pointers
std::vector<Base*> devices;
// Or in modern C++: std::vector<std::unique_ptr<Base>> devices;
```

**The core rule:** Slicing happens when a Derived object is **copied into a Base value**. The Derived-specific data and vtable are lost. It's silent — no compiler warning by default. To use polymorphism correctly, always use **pointers or references** to base types, never values.

