#include <stdio.h>

typedef struct { int version_id; const char *name; } FwEntry;

// Exact match: returns index or -1
int fw_search(FwEntry *table, int n, int target) {
    int lo = 0, hi = n - 1;
    while (lo <= hi) {
        int mid = lo + (hi - lo) / 2;  // Avoids overflow!
        if (table[mid].version_id == target) return mid;
        else if (table[mid].version_id < target) lo = mid + 1;
        else hi = mid - 1;
    }
    return -1;
}

// Lower bound: returns first index where version_id >= target
int fw_lower_bound(FwEntry *table, int n, int target) {
    int lo = 0, hi = n;
    while (lo < hi) {
        int mid = lo + (hi - lo) / 2;
        if (table[mid].version_id < target) lo = mid + 1;
        else hi = mid;
    }
    return lo;  // Insertion point
}
```

**Key details:**
- `mid = lo + (hi - lo) / 2` prevents integer overflow that `(lo + hi) / 2` can cause on 32-bit systems when lo + hi > INT_MAX
- Lower bound returns `n` if target is larger than all elements (valid insertion point)
- O(log n) — for a 1024-entry register map, max 10 comparisons vs 1024 for linear scan

**Firmware uses:**
- Bootloader: search version compatibility table during OTA update
- Error code lookup: binary search sorted error code → string table
- Register map: find register descriptor by address in sorted peripheral table
- Sorted interrupt vector lookup in configurable interrupt controllers

