#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdint.h>
#include <string.h>

#define CRC32_POLY 0xEDB88320  // Reversed polynomial (bit-reversed 0x04C11DB7)

static uint32_t crc_table[256];

void crc32_init_table(void) {
    for (uint32_t i = 0; i < 256; i++) {
        uint32_t crc = i;
        for (int j = 0; j < 8; j++) {
            if (crc & 1)
                crc = (crc >> 1) ^ CRC32_POLY;
            else
                crc >>= 1;
        }
        crc_table[i] = crc;
    }
}

uint32_t crc32(const uint8_t *data, size_t len) {
    uint32_t crc = 0xFFFFFFFF;  // Init value
    for (size_t i = 0; i < len; i++) {
        uint8_t index = (crc ^ data[i]) & 0xFF;
        crc = (crc >> 8) ^ crc_table[index];
    }
    return crc ^ 0xFFFFFFFF;  // Final XOR
}
```

**How the lookup table works:**
Instead of processing each bit individually (slow), we precompute the CRC contribution of every possible byte value. Each byte of input requires just one table lookup + XOR + shift instead of 8 iterations.

**Performance:** 1 table lookup per byte vs 8 iterations per byte = ~4-8x speedup. The 1KB table easily fits in L1 cache.

**Standard test vector:** CRC-32 of ASCII "123456789" = 0xCBF43926

**Firmware uses:**
- Flash integrity: CRC stored in flash header, verified at boot
- OTA updates: validate firmware image before flashing
- Protocol frames: Ethernet FCS, USB packets, storage block checksums
- EEPROM wear detection: CRC detects bit-rot in stored config

