#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>
#include <time.h>
#include <string.h>

#define N 32768

int cmp_int(const void *a, const void *b) {
    return *(int*)a - *(int*)b;
}

int main() {
    int *data = malloc(N * sizeof(int));
    srand(42);
    for (int i = 0; i < N; i++)
        data[i] = rand() % 256;

    // Unsorted
    long long sum1 = 0;
    clock_t t0 = clock();
    for (int iter = 0; iter < 10000; iter++)
        for (int i = 0; i < N; i++)
            if (data[i] >= 128) sum1 += data[i];
    clock_t t1 = clock();

    // Sort, then same loop
    qsort(data, N, sizeof(int), cmp_int);
    long long sum2 = 0;
    clock_t t2 = clock();
    for (int iter = 0; iter < 10000; iter++)
        for (int i = 0; i < N; i++)
            if (data[i] >= 128) sum2 += data[i];
    clock_t t3 = clock();

    printf("Unsorted: %.3f sec (sum=%lld)\n",
           (double)(t1-t0)/CLOCKS_PER_SEC, sum1);
    printf("Sorted:   %.3f sec (sum=%lld)\n",
           (double)(t3-t2)/CLOCKS_PER_SEC, sum2);
    printf("Sums match: %s\n", sum1 == sum2 ? "yes" : "no");
    free(data);
}
```

**Why sorted is faster (branch prediction):**

Modern CPUs predict branch outcomes speculatively. The `if (data[i] >= 128)` branch has two patterns:

- **Unsorted:** TTFFTFTFFTTFFT... — random, ~50% misprediction rate. Each misprediction costs ~15-20 cycles (pipeline flush).
- **Sorted:** FFFFFFFFFF...TTTTTTTTT — long runs of same outcome. Predictor locks on. Misprediction only at the boundary (~1 time total).

With 32K elements × 10K iterations × ~50% mispredict × ~15 cycles = billions of wasted cycles for unsorted.

**Firmware relevance:**
- Sensor data filtering (threshold checks in tight ISR loops)
- Packet classification (if/else chains in protocol parsers)
- Display pipeline: alpha blending conditionals on per-pixel loops

**Fix without sorting:** Use branchless code:
```c
// Branchless: no branch prediction dependency
int mask = -(data[i] >= 128); // All 1s or all 0s
sum += data[i] & mask;
```

